 name beginning with <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’).","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>lond</i> ‘land’ (Old English <i>gāra</i> + <i>land</i>, <i>lond</i>), for someone who lived ‘(at the) triangular piece of land’. Compare   Garfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerland","meanings":["English (North Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Garland  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Garfield","meanings":["English (Midlands): topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country, field’ (Old English <i>gār</i> + <i>feld</i>), for someone who lived by a triangular piece of land.","English: alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Carville   (a name of Norman origin), with excrescent final <i>-d</i>.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Gartland","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Garland  .","Irish (northern Leinster and southern Ulster): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Mac Gearnúin</b>, a patronymic from the Norman personal name   Gernon  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Anseau","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adelard, Francois, Jean Pierre, Normand.","French: variant of   Manceau  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Manceau","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French: habitational name for someone from Mans, a region in Sarthe, or from Maine, a former province in the northwestern part of France. Compare   Manseau   and English   Mansell   1."]}]},{"name":"III","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Yuko, Aiko, Hideaki, Hiroki, Hiroyuki, Isamu, Kaoru, Katsumi, Keiichiro, Kenji, Masako, Masayuki.","Japanese: variously written, sometimes with characters used phonetically; the most probable meanings are 仁井 ‘benevolent well’, 新居 ‘new residence’, or 新井 ‘new well’. It is not common in Japan."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anseau III de Garlande de Tournan-en-Brie was born in 1152, in Tournan-en-Brie, Melun, Seine-et-Marne, France, his father, Anseau II de Garlande seigneur de La Houssaye, was 46 and his mother, Dame Rancie Renee du MESNIL-AUBRI ou Rance du Mesnil-Amelot Du Mesnil-Aubri, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Sophie d'Aspremont. He died in 1200, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1152–1200":"1152–1200","1163–1208":"1163–1208","–1220":"–1220","1145–1207":"1145–1207","1197–1248":"1197–1248","1106–1188":"1106–1188","1130–1192":"1130–1192","1220":"1220","1197":"1197","1152":"1152","1130":"1130","1163":"1163","1192":"1192","1106":"1106","1248":"1248","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1188":"1188","1208":"1208","1207":"1207","Tournan-en-Brie, Melun, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Tournan-en-Brie, Melun, Seine-et-Marne, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1152–1200":"1152–1200","1163–1208":"1163–1208","–1220":"–1220","1145–1207":"1145–1207","1197–1248":"1197–1248","1106–1188":"1106–1188","1130–1192":"1130–1192","1220":"1220","1197":"1197","1152":"1152","1130":"1130","1163":"1163","1192":"1192","1106":"1106","1248":"1248","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1188":"1188","12